            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Autograd becomes important once a tensor represents something trainable, such as a weight. When `requires_grad=True`, PyTorch remembers the operations used to produce a result. After you call `backward()`, PyTorch fills `.grad` on the leaf tensors that need updates."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "A useful mental model is that autograd builds a computation history while your code runs forward. Then `backward()` walks that history in reverse to compute gradients. You usually do not need to derive those gradients by hand, but you do need to know which tensors should track them."},
