            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "A useful rule: leaf tensors are the original tensors you created directly, like `x` and `y`. Those are the tensors whose `.grad` fields PyTorch usually fills after `backward()`. Intermediate tensors like `u` or `v` usually have a `grad_fn`, but their `.grad` is not kept unless you explicitly ask for it."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Leaf tensor idea", "content": "x = torch.tensor(2.0, requires_grad=True)\ny = x**2\nprint(x.grad_fn)  # None, because x is a leaf tensor\nprint(y.grad_fn)  # has a backward function because y came from an operation"},
