            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "There is one more subtle point: gradients accumulate in `.grad`. If you call `backward()` twice without clearing `.grad`, PyTorch adds the new gradient on top of the old one. That is useful in some advanced cases, but in a normal training loop you usually want to zero the gradient before the next step."},
