            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Logistic regression still starts with a linear formula, but now you interpret the output as a probability by applying sigmoid to the raw logit."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Probability path", "content": "logits = x @ weight + bias\nprobs = torch.sigmoid(logits)"},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Important distinction", "content": "A logit is any real number. A probability must lie between 0 and 1."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Regression predicts continuous values like price or temperature. Logistic regression predicts the probability of one class, often written as 0 vs 1. The math starts similarly, but the interpretation is different."},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Classification pipeline", "items": ["Compute a linear score called a logit.", "Apply sigmoid to convert the logit to a probability.", "Compare that probability to the true label.", "Use binary cross-entropy to penalize wrong confident predictions."]},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Thresholding probabilities", "content": "probs = torch.sigmoid(logits)\npreds = (probs >= 0.5).float()"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Sigmoid takes any real number and squashes it into the range 0 to 1. Large positive logits become probabilities near 1. Large negative logits become probabilities near 0. A logit of 0 maps to probability 0.5, which sits right at the decision boundary."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Reading logits", "content": "torch.sigmoid(torch.tensor([-4.0, 0.0, 4.0]))\n# tensor close to [0.018, 0.500, 0.982]"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "That is why the sign of the logit matters so much. Positive logit pushes the prediction toward class 1. Negative logit pushes it toward class 0. The larger the magnitude, the more confident the model is."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Binary cross-entropy becomes very large when the model is confidently wrong. If the true label is 1 but the model predicts a probability close to 0, the loss should strongly punish that mistake."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Manual BCE idea", "content": "preds = preds.clamp(1e-7, 1 - 1e-7)\nloss = -(targets * torch.log(preds) + (1 - targets) * torch.log(1 - preds)).mean()"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The BCE formula has two parts. One part is active when the label is 1 and asks the model to make `log(pred)` large, which means `pred` should be close to 1. The other part is active when the label is 0 and asks the model to make `log(1 - pred)` large, which means `pred` should be close to 0."},
            {"type": "math", "title": "BCE In Math Form", "content": "BCE = -[y log(p) + (1 - y) log(1 - p)]"},
            {"type": "list", "title": "How to read class outputs", "items": ["Probability near 0 means strong belief in class 0.", "Probability near 1 means strong belief in class 1.", "Probability near 0.5 means the model is uncertain.", "Thresholding converts probabilities into hard class decisions."]},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Making binary labels", "content": "scores = torch.tensor([-2.0, 0.3, 1.7])\nlabels = (scores > 0).float().unsqueeze(1)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Classification labels are usually stored as 0 and 1. The model does not directly emit those labels during training. It emits probabilities, because probabilities provide a smoother learning signal for gradient-based optimization."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "This matters for gradients too. A hard threshold like `(probs >= 0.5)` is fine for evaluation, but it is not the object you want inside the training loss. The smooth probability is what lets gradient-based learning work well."},
            {"type": "math", "title": "Sigmoid At Zero", "content": "σ(z) = 1 / (1 + e⁻ᶻ)\nσ(0) = 1 / (1 + e⁰)\n     = 1 / (1 + 1)\n     = 1/2 = 0.5"},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Worked example: logistic probability and threshold", "content": "logits = torch.tensor([[-2.0], [0.0], [2.0]])\nprobs = torch.sigmoid(logits)\npreds = (probs >= 0.5).float()"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "That worked example shows the full interpretation chain: raw score -> probability -> hard class. During learning, the probability is the important smooth quantity. During reporting, the hard class is often what people want to see."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Common mistakes in manual logistic regression", "content": "Using hard thresholded predictions inside the training loss, forgetting that probabilities must lie in `[0, 1]`, and mixing up logits with probabilities are the most common mistakes."},
