            {"type": "callout", "title": "Why clamping matters", "content": "If a predicted probability becomes exactly 0 or 1, taking a log can cause numerical trouble. Clamping avoids `log(0)` in the manual formula."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Why probabilities help learning", "content": "A hard 0 or 1 class prediction throws away uncertainty. A probability like 0.62 tells you much more about how the model currently feels, which makes it more useful inside a differentiable loss."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Common confusion", "content": "A class prediction like 0 or 1 is not the same thing as a probability. The probability is the model's confidence before thresholding."},
