            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "In PyTorch you usually return raw logits from forward() and let BCEWithLogitsLoss handle the stable sigmoid-plus-loss computation during training."},
            {"type": "list", "title": "What to remember", "items": ["forward() returns logits, not probabilities", "torch.sigmoid is for interpretation during evaluation", "labels should match the output shape"]},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "This chapter repeats the previous classification idea with PyTorch's standard building blocks. The key improvement is numerical stability. `BCEWithLogitsLoss` combines the sigmoid step and the BCE calculation in a way that is more stable than manually doing both during training."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Standard model and loss", "content": "model = nn.Linear(2, 1)\nloss_fn = nn.BCEWithLogitsLoss()\nlogits = model(x)\nloss = loss_fn(logits, y)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "This is a good example of a common PyTorch design pattern: keep the model output simple and let the loss function handle the numerically tricky transformation. That is why many models return logits, not already-processed probabilities."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Notice the difference between training and evaluation. During training, the loss function wants logits. During evaluation, a human usually wants probabilities or class labels, so you apply `torch.sigmoid` yourself after the forward pass."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Evaluation flow", "content": "logits = model(x)\nprobs = torch.sigmoid(logits)\npreds = (probs >= 0.5).float()"},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Why this pattern is preferred", "items": ["The model stays simple: it only returns logits.", "The loss function handles the numerically sensitive part.", "You can still turn logits into probabilities when you want to inspect predictions."]},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Numerical stability sounds abstract, but the practical idea is simple: some formulas are mathematically correct yet fragile on a computer. `BCEWithLogitsLoss` uses a more stable internal form than manually doing `sigmoid` followed by `log`, especially for very large positive or negative logits."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "In practice, this pattern scales from logistic regression to much larger neural networks. Even deep classifiers often return logits first, and the training loss is responsible for converting them into a stable objective."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Logits to probabilities", "content": "logits = torch.tensor([[-1.0], [0.0], [1.0]])\nprobs = torch.sigmoid(logits)\npreds = (probs >= 0.5).float()"},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Typical training step", "content": "logits = model(batch_x)\nloss = loss_fn(logits, batch_y)\noptimizer.zero_grad()\nloss.backward()\noptimizer.step()"},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Train vs evaluate checklist", "items": ["Training: model returns logits.", "Training: use BCEWithLogitsLoss on those logits.", "Evaluation: apply sigmoid if you want probabilities.", "Evaluation: threshold probabilities if you want hard class predictions."]},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "A useful way to think about this chapter is that the model and the loss have a contract. The model promises to output logits. The loss promises to interpret those logits correctly during training. Breaking that contract is what causes the common double-sigmoid mistake."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Correct separation of responsibilities", "content": "class Model(nn.Module):\n    def forward(self, x):\n        return self.linear(x)   # logits only\n\nloss = nn.BCEWithLogitsLoss()(logits, labels)"},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Worked example: stable classification training step", "content": "model = nn.Linear(2, 1)\nloss_fn = nn.BCEWithLogitsLoss()\noptimizer = torch.optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=0.1)\n\nlogits = model(batch_x)\nloss = loss_fn(logits, batch_y)\noptimizer.zero_grad()\nloss.backward()\noptimizer.step()"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "This chapter is really about separating concerns cleanly. The model returns logits. The loss handles training-time stability. Evaluation code turns logits into probabilities and class labels only when needed."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Common mistakes with BCEWithLogitsLoss", "content": "Applying sigmoid inside `forward()`, passing labels with the wrong shape, and confusing evaluation-time probabilities with training-time logits are the most common mistakes."},
