            {"type": "math", "title": "LSTM Gate Sketch", "content": "f_t = σ(W_f [h_{t-1}, x_t] + b_f)\ni_t = σ(W_i [h_{t-1}, x_t] + b_i)\no_t = σ(W_o [h_{t-1}, x_t] + b_o)\n\\tilde{c}_t = tanh(W_c [h_{t-1}, x_t] + b_c)\nc_t = f_t ⊙ c_{t-1} + i_t ⊙ \\tilde{c}_t\nh_t = o_t ⊙ tanh(c_t)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "You do not need to memorize every gate equation immediately, but the structure is worth seeing once. The forget gate decides what old information to keep, the input gate decides what new information to write, and the output gate decides what part of the memory becomes the visible hidden state."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "In this one-layer LSTM, `hidden_state[-1]` is the last layer's final hidden state, so it has shape `(batch, hidden_size)`. That makes it a convenient summary vector for sequence classification."},
